 Outstanding Federal Trial Judge Award, the Thurgood Marshall Award from the Section on Individual Rights and Responsibilities of the American Bar Association, and the Morris Dees Justice Award from the University of Alabama School of Law. This paperback reprint of William Wayne Justice chronicles his judicial career and the decisions he reached. It includes a new epilogue that describes Justice's move to Austin as a judge on senior status yet with a full caseload, tracks the long-running institutional reform cases to their conclusion, and examines the legacy of this remarkable and controversial jurist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aJudges -- Texas -- Biography. 0aJudges -- United States -- Biography. 0aJudgeszTexasvBiography. 0aJudgeszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJustice, William Wayne, -- 1920-2009. 0aPolitical questions and judicial power -- Texas. 0aPolitical questions and judicial power -- United States. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzTexas. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzUnited States. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311074534440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71905740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292743724423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292743724/original  a978-3-11-074534-4  University of Texas Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles